   8     "RequirementInformation", ["requirement", "parent"]

  12 class ResolverException(Exception):
  13     """A base class for all exceptions raised by this module.
  14 
  15     Exceptions derived by this class should all be handled in this module. Any
  16     bubbling pass the resolver should be treated as a bug.
  17     """
  18 
  19 
  20 class RequirementsConflicted(ResolverException):
  21     def __init__(self, criterion):
  22         super(RequirementsConflicted, self).__init__(criterion)
  23         self.criterion = criterion
  24 
  25     def __str__(self):
  26         return "Requirements conflict: {}".format(
  27             ", ".join(repr(r) for r in self.criterion.iter_requirement()),
  28         )
  29 
  30 
  31 class InconsistentCandidate(ResolverException):
  32     def __init__(self, candidate, criterion):
  33         super(InconsistentCandidate, self).__init__(candidate, criterion)
  34         self.candidate = candidate
  35         self.criterion = criterion
  36 
  37     def __str__(self):
  38         return "Provided candidate {!r} does not satisfy {}".format(
  39             self.candidate,
  40             ", ".join(repr(r) for r in self.criterion.iter_requirement()),
  41         )
  42

  44 class Criterion(object):
  45     """Representation of possible resolution results of a package.
  46 
  47     This holds three attributes:
  48 
  49     * `information` is a collection of `RequirementInformation` pairs.
  50       Each pair is a requirement contributing to this criterion, and the
  51       candidate that provides the requirement.
  52     * `incompatibilities` is a collection of all known not-to-work candidates
  53       to exclude from consideration.
  54     * `candidates` is a collection containing all possible candidates deducted
  55       from the union of contributing requirements and known incompatibilities.
  56       It should never be empty, except when the criterion is an attribute of a
  57       raised `RequirementsConflicted` (in which case it is always empty).
  58 
  59     .. note::
  60         This class is intended to be externally immutable. **Do not** mutate
  61         any of its attribute containers.
  62     """
  63 
  64     def __init__(self, candidates, information, incompatibilities):
  65         self.candidates = candidates
  66         self.information = information
  67         self.incompatibilities = incompatibilities
  68 
  69     def __repr__(self):
  70         requirements = ", ".join(
  71             "{!r} from {!r}".format(req, parent)
  72             for req, parent in self.information
  73         )
  74         return "<Criterion {}>".format(requirements)
  75 
  76     @classmethod
  77     def from_requirement(cls, provider, requirement, parent):
  78         """Build an instance from a requirement.
  79         """
  80         candidates = provider.find_matches(requirement)
  81         criterion = cls(
  82             candidates=candidates,
  83             information=[RequirementInformation(requirement, parent)],
  84             incompatibilities=[],
  85         )
  86         if not candidates:
  87             raise RequirementsConflicted(criterion)
  88         return criterion
  89 
  90     def iter_requirement(self):
  91         return (i.requirement for i in self.information)
  92 
  93     def iter_parent(self):
  94         return (i.parent for i in self.information)
  95 
  96     def merged_with(self, provider, requirement, parent):
  97         """Build a new instance from this and a new requirement.
  98         """
  99         infos = list(self.information)
 100         infos.append(RequirementInformation(requirement, parent))
 101         candidates = [
 102             c
 103             for c in self.candidates
 104             if provider.is_satisfied_by(requirement, c)
 105         ]
 106         criterion = type(self)(candidates, infos, list(self.incompatibilities))
 107         if not candidates:
 108             raise RequirementsConflicted(criterion)
 109         return criterion
 110 
 111     def excluded_of(self, candidate):
 112         """Build a new instance from this, but excluding specified candidate.
 113 
 114         Returns the new instance, or None if we still have no valid candidates.
 115         """
 116         incompats = list(self.incompatibilities)
 117         incompats.append(candidate)
 118         candidates = [c for c in self.candidates if c != candidate]
 119         if not candidates:
 120             return None
 121         criterion = type(self)(candidates, list(self.information), incompats)
 122         return criterion
 123

 129 class ResolutionImpossible(ResolutionError):
 130     def __init__(self, causes):
 131         super(ResolutionImpossible, self).__init__(causes)
 132         # causes is a list of RequirementInformation objects
 133         self.causes = causes

 136 class ResolutionTooDeep(ResolutionError):
 137     def __init__(self, round_count):
 138         super(ResolutionTooDeep, self).__init__(round_count)
 139         self.round_count = round_count

 142 # Resolution state in a round.
 143 State = collections.namedtuple("State", "mapping criteria")
 144 
 145 
 146 class Resolution(object):
 147     """Stateful resolution object.
 148 
 149     This is designed as a one-off object that holds information to kick start
 150     the resolution process, and holds the results afterwards.
 151     """
 152 
 153     def __init__(self, provider, reporter):
 154         self._p = provider
 155         self._r = reporter
 156         self._states = []
 157 
 158     @property
 159     def state(self):
 160         try:
 161             return self._states[-1]
 162         except IndexError:
 163             raise AttributeError("state")
 164 
 165     def _push_new_state(self):
 166         """Push a new state into history.
 167 
 168         This new state will be used to hold resolution results of the next
 169         coming round.
 170         """
 171         try:
 172             base = self._states[-1]
 173         except IndexError:
 174             state = State(mapping=collections.OrderedDict(), criteria={})
 175         else:
 176             state = State(
 177                 mapping=base.mapping.copy(), criteria=base.criteria.copy(),
 178             )
 179         self._states.append(state)
 180 
 181     def _merge_into_criterion(self, requirement, parent):
 182         self._r.adding_requirement(requirement)
 183         name = self._p.identify(requirement)
 184         try:
 185             crit = self.state.criteria[name]
 186         except KeyError:
 187             crit = Criterion.from_requirement(self._p, requirement, parent)
 188         else:
 189             crit = crit.merged_with(self._p, requirement, parent)
 190         return name, crit
 191 
 192     def _get_criterion_item_preference(self, item):
 193         name, criterion = item
 194         try:
 195             pinned = self.state.mapping[name]
 196         except KeyError:
 197             pinned = None
 198         return self._p.get_preference(
 199             pinned, criterion.candidates, criterion.information,
 200         )
 201 
 202     def _is_current_pin_satisfying(self, name, criterion):
 203         try:
 204             current_pin = self.state.mapping[name]
 205         except KeyError:
 206             return False
 207         return all(
 208             self._p.is_satisfied_by(r, current_pin)
 209             for r in criterion.iter_requirement()
 210         )
 211 
 212     def _get_criteria_to_update(self, candidate):
 213         criteria = {}
 214         for r in self._p.get_dependencies(candidate):
 215             name, crit = self._merge_into_criterion(r, parent=candidate)
 216             criteria[name] = crit
 217         return criteria
 218 
 219     def _attempt_to_pin_criterion(self, name, criterion):
 220         causes = []
 221         for candidate in reversed(criterion.candidates):
 222             try:
 223                 criteria = self._get_criteria_to_update(candidate)
 224             except RequirementsConflicted as e:
 225                 causes.append(e.criterion)
 226                 continue
 227 
 228             # Put newly-pinned candidate at the end. This is essential because
 229             # backtracking looks at this mapping to get the last pin.
 230             self._r.pinning(candidate)
 231             self.state.mapping.pop(name, None)
 232             self.state.mapping[name] = candidate
 233             self.state.criteria.update(criteria)
 234 
 235             # Check the newly-pinned candidate actually works. This should
 236             # always pass under normal circumstances, but in the case of a
 237             # faulty provider, we will raise an error to notify the implementer
 238             # to fix find_matches() and/or is_satisfied_by().
 239             if not self._is_current_pin_satisfying(name, criterion):
 240                 raise InconsistentCandidate(candidate, criterion)
 241 
 242             return []
 243 
 244         # All candidates tried, nothing works. This criterion is a dead
 245         # end, signal for backtracking.
 246         return causes
 247 
 248     def _backtrack(self):
 249         # We need at least 3 states here:
 250         # (a) One known not working, to drop.
 251         # (b) One to backtrack to.
 252         # (c) One to restore state (b) to its state prior to candidate-pinning,
 253         #     so we can pin another one instead.
 254         while len(self._states) >= 3:
 255             del self._states[-1]
 256 
 257             # Retract the last candidate pin, and create a new (b).
 258             name, candidate = self._states.pop().mapping.popitem()
 259             self._r.backtracking(candidate)
 260             self._push_new_state()
 261 
 262             # Mark the retracted candidate as incompatible.
 263             criterion = self.state.criteria[name].excluded_of(candidate)
 264             if criterion is None:
 265                 # This state still does not work. Try the still previous state.
 266                 continue
 267             self.state.criteria[name] = criterion
 268 
 269             return True
 270 
 271         return False
 272 
 273     def resolve(self, requirements, max_rounds):
 274         if self._states:
 275             raise RuntimeError("already resolved")
 276 
 277         self._push_new_state()
 278         for r in requirements:
 279             try:
 280                 name, crit = self._merge_into_criterion(r, parent=None)
 281             except RequirementsConflicted as e:
 282                 raise ResolutionImpossible(e.criterion.information)
 283             self.state.criteria[name] = crit
 284 
 285         self._r.starting()
 286 
 287         for round_index in range(max_rounds):
 288             self._r.starting_round(round_index)
 289 
 290             self._push_new_state()
 291             curr = self.state
 292 
 293             unsatisfied_criterion_items = [
 294                 item
 295                 for item in self.state.criteria.items()
 296                 if not self._is_current_pin_satisfying(*item)
 297             ]
 298 
 299             # All criteria are accounted for. Nothing more to pin, we are done!
 300             if not unsatisfied_criterion_items:
 301                 del self._states[-1]
 302                 self._r.ending(curr)
 303                 return self.state
 304 
 305             # Choose the most preferred unpinned criterion to try.
 306             name, criterion = min(
 307                 unsatisfied_criterion_items,
 308                 key=self._get_criterion_item_preference,
 309             )
 310             failure_causes = self._attempt_to_pin_criterion(name, criterion)
 311 
 312             # Backtrack if pinning fails.
 313             if failure_causes:
 314                 result = self._backtrack()
 315                 if not result:
 316                     causes = [
 317                         i for crit in failure_causes for i in crit.information
 318                     ]
 319                     raise ResolutionImpossible(causes)
 320 
 321             self._r.ending_round(round_index, curr)
 322 
 323         raise ResolutionTooDeep(max_rounds)
 324 
 325 
 326 def _has_route_to_root(criteria, key, all_keys, connected):
 327     if key in connected:
 328         return True
 329     if key not in criteria:
 330         return False
 331     for p in criteria[key].iter_parent():
 332         try:
 333             pkey = all_keys[id(p)]
 334         except KeyError:
 335             continue
 336         if pkey in connected:
 337             connected.add(key)
 338             return True
 339         if _has_route_to_root(criteria, pkey, all_keys, connected):
 340             connected.add(key)
 341             return True
 342     return False
 343 
 344 
 345 Result = collections.namedtuple("Result", "mapping graph criteria")
 346 
 347 
 348 def _build_result(state):
 349     mapping = state.mapping
 350     all_keys = {id(v): k for k, v in mapping.items()}
 351     all_keys[id(None)] = None
 352 
 353     graph = DirectedGraph()
 354     graph.add(None)  # Sentinel as root dependencies' parent.
 355 
 356     connected = {None}
 357     for key, criterion in state.criteria.items():
 358         if not _has_route_to_root(state.criteria, key, all_keys, connected):
 359             continue
 360         if key not in graph:
 361             graph.add(key)
 362         for p in criterion.iter_parent():
 363             try:
 364                 pkey = all_keys[id(p)]
 365             except KeyError:
 366                 continue
 367             if pkey not in graph:
 368                 graph.add(pkey)
 369             graph.connect(pkey, key)
 370 
 371     return Result(
 372         mapping={k: v for k, v in mapping.items() if k in connected},
 373         graph=graph,
 374         criteria=state.criteria,
 375     )

 378 class Resolver(AbstractResolver):
 379     """The thing that performs the actual resolution work.
 380     """
 381 
 382     base_exception = ResolverException
 383 
 384     def resolve(self, requirements, max_rounds=100):
 385         """Take a collection of constraints, spit out the resolution result.
 386 
 387         The return value is a representation to the final resolution result. It
 388         is a tuple subclass with three public members:
 389 
 390         * `mapping`: A dict of resolved candidates. Each key is an identifier
 391             of a requirement (as returned by the provider's `identify` method),
 392             and the value is the resolved candidate.
 393         * `graph`: A `DirectedGraph` instance representing the dependency tree.
 394             The vertices are keys of `mapping`, and each edge represents *why*
 395             a particular package is included. A special vertex `None` is
 396             included to represent parents of user-supplied requirements.
 397         * `criteria`: A dict of "criteria" that hold detailed information on
 398             how edges in the graph are derived. Each key is an identifier of a
 399             requirement, and the value is a `Criterion` instance.
 400 
 401         The following exceptions may be raised if a resolution cannot be found:
 402 
 403         * `ResolutionImpossible`: A resolution cannot be found for the given
 404             combination of requirements. The `causes` attribute of the
 405             exception is a list of (requirement, parent), giving the
 406             requirements that could not be satisfied.
 407         * `ResolutionTooDeep`: The dependency tree is too deeply nested and
 408             the resolver gave up. This is usually caused by a circular
 409             dependency, but you can try to resolve this by increasing the
 410             `max_rounds` argument.
 411         """
 412         resolution = Resolution(self.provider, self.reporter)
 413         state = resolution.resolve(requirements, max_rounds=max_rounds)
 414         return _build_result(state)
